      <div xml:id="NA215-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu pakaṟkuṟi vantu mīḷvāṉai “avaḷ āṟṟun taṉmaiyaḷ allaḷ nīr (EN, ER, ET: nīyir) iṅkut taṅkal pālīr. emarum iṉṉatoru tavaṟṟiṉar” eṉat tōḻi talaimakaṟkuc colliyatu. 2. iravukkuṟi maṟuttu varaivu kaṭāyatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is what the confidante said to HIM who was returning after having come to the day tryst: “It is your fate to support here the one who does not have her ow people who are able [to do so] for her. Our people are at fault in this respect.” 2. It is also urging for marriage by refusing the night tryst.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA215">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kuṇakaṭa livarntu kurūukkatir parappip</l>
<l>            pakalkeḻu celvaṉ kuṭamalai maṟaiyap</l>
<l>            pulampuvan tiṟutta puṉkaṇ mālai</l>
<l>            yilaṅkuvaḷai makaḷir viyaṉaka rayara</l>
<l>            mīṉiṇan tokutta vūṉey yoṇcuṭar </l>
<l>            nīṉiṟap parappiṟ ṟayaṅkutirai yutaippak</l>
<l>            karaicēr pirunta kalleṉ pākkat</l>
<l>            tiṉṟunī yivaṇai yāki yemmoṭu</l>
<l>            taṅki ṉevaṉō teyya ceṅkōṟ</l>
<l>            koṭumuṭi yavvalai pariyap pōkiya </l>
<l>            kōṭcuṟāk kuṟitta muṉpoṭu</l>
<l>            vēṭṭam vāyā temarvā ralarē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent3">Since you [are] here today,</l>
<l rend="indent">in the noisy village that lies close to the shore,</l>
<l rend="indent2">while the glittering waves are dashing in the blue-coloured extension,</l>
<l rend="indent">with bright lights of musty<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ūṉ</term> might refer here to the state of the oil which is not yet purified from remnants of flesh.</note> oil collected from the fat of the fish,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when women with shining bangles are engaged in the wide mansions in</l>
<l rend="indent">[the tasks of] sorrowful evening that has come [and] tarries with loneliness,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when the day-owning goer<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">celvaṉ</term>, clearly is a metaphor for the sun, but does it mean the one who is constantly moving or one who is rich, since he owns the day? And is the high class suffix -<term xml:lang="ta">aṉ</term> a reason to suppose that it refers to the sun god rather than the sun?</note>, after having climbed over the east sea</l>
<l rend="indent2">[and] spreading his brilliant beams, vanishes behind</l>
<l rend="indent2">the western mountains,</l>
<l>– what if [you] stayed with us?</l>
<l>Our people won’t come unless the hunt succeeds,</l>
<l rend="indent">with a strength that has put [its] intention on the killing shark</l>
<l rend="indent2">that was gone, so that the pretty net with bent knots [and] straight rod<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kōl</term> is one of the formulaic epithets of a net, and it certainly refers to one of the elements the net is made of - some sort of canes then? Since it is straight, it might be supposed to be the handle of the net. In any case, the <term xml:lang="ta">ceṅkāl</term> printed in EN seems to make less sense.</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">had been damaged.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
